BriefingText:
BRIEFING

The mission of Project Mercury is the projection of a manned capsule into a semi-permanent orbit about the earth, the study of man's capabilities in space flight, and the subsequent safe return of the capsule and its occupant to the earth's surface. 

In this first manned flight, you will fly the Mercury space capsule into a sub-orbital trajectory with an altitude of between 170-190 km, and splash down in the Atlantic just North East of the Bahamas.

You will be weightless for about 5 minutes where you will perform the following activities.
1) Flight controls test
2) Periscope sightseeing

The retrograde engines will fire automatically and you will shortly after perform an atmospheric reentry & landing.
Description: MR-3 was the first manned mission of the Mercury program, where the first American was launched into a sub-orbital trajectory with a splashdown in the Atlantic. It was piloted by astronaut Alan Shepard.

MissionActivities.Description: Perform the manual flight controls test.

Steps.Description: Return to roll 0°, pitch -10° and yaw 0°

MissionActivities.Title: Flight Controls Test

MissionActivities.Description: Attain +14 degrees pitch, 0 roll and 0 yaw initially, and observe Earth through the periscope, modify attitude as required.

Steps.Description: Maneuver to the attitude +14° pitch, 0° yaw and 0° roll
Look down at the periscope, observe the Earth, adjust attitude as needed.

MissionActivities.Title: Earth observation test

MissionCommands.Message: We are currently 5 minutes from launch. Todays flight will take you into an sub-orbital flight with an altitude of 180km, and splashdown in the Atlantic oceean.

{{capsuleName}} this is Indian Cap Com, do you read me?
Affirmative Indian Cap Com, let me give you a report. I'm at 7,000 feet, the main chute is good, the landing bag is on green, my peroxide has dumped, my condition is good.
Roger {{capsuleName}}, I understand you're at 7000 feet, your main chute is open, over
Ahh, this is Seven. Relay back to Cap Com please. My altitude now 4,000 feet, condition as before, the main chute is good, the landing bag has deployed, the peroxide has dumped
I'm about 1,500 feet now. The main chute still looks good. The rate of descent is indicating 30 ft/sec.
Roger, pickup on the way. Over, good job.
